🔹 What is Virtualization?

Virtualization means creating a virtual (not real physical) version of something — like a server, operating system, or storage.

In simple words:
👉 One physical computer can run many virtual computers.

How it works:

We use software called a hypervisor.

The hypervisor creates multiple Virtual Machines (VMs).

Each VM has:

Its own OS (Windows/Linux)

CPU, RAM, Storage (virtual)

Example:

Using Oracle VM VirtualBox or VMware Workstation, you can install:

Windows inside Linux

Linux inside Windows

Diagram idea:

Physical Machine → Hypervisor → VM1 (Linux) + VM2 (Windows)

🔹 What is Containerization?

Containerization is a lightweight way to run applications.

Instead of creating full virtual machines, containers share the same OS kernel but keep applications isolated.

👉 Containers package:

Application

Libraries

Dependencies

Example:

Using Docker, you can run:

Nginx server

MySQL

Node.js app
inside separate containers on the same system.

Diagram idea:

Physical Machine → OS → Docker → Container1 + Container2

🔥 Main Difference Between Virtualization and Containerization
Feature	Virtualization	Containerization
OS	Each VM has its own OS	Share same OS
Size	Heavy (GBs)	Lightweight (MBs)
Speed	Slower boot	Very fast
Resource Usage	High	Low
Example	VirtualBox	Docker
🧠 Simple Example

Think like this:

🏠 Virtualization = Many separate houses (each has full setup)

🏢 Containerization = Apartments in one building (share structure)

